To fix the SQL Injection vulnerability in the provided Java code snippet, you should use PreparedStatement instead of Statement. PreparedStatement allows you to safely pass user input as parameters without directly concatenating it into the SQL query string.

Here is the updated and secure version of the code:

```java
import java.sql.Connection;
import java.sql.DriverManager;
import java.sql.PreparedStatement;
import java.sql.ResultSet;
import java.util.Scanner;

public class SecureSQLInjectionExample {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
            System.out.println("Enter a user ID to search: ");
            String userInput = scanner.nextLine();

            Connection connection = DriverManager.getConnection("jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/mydatabase", "username", "password");

            // Using PreparedStatement to avoid SQL Injection
            String query = "SELECT * FROM users WHERE id=?";
            PreparedStatement preparedStatement = connection.prepareStatement(query);
            preparedStatement.setString(1, userInput);

            ResultSet resultSet = preparedStatement.executeQuery();

            while (resultSet.next()) {
                System.out.println("User found: " + resultSet.getString("username"));
            }

            preparedStatement.close();
            connection.close();
        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
``

